  "topic_name": "Matter - States and Changes",
  "canonical_explanation": {
    "text": "Matter exists in three states: solid (definite shape and volume, tightly packed particles), liquid (definite volume but takes container shape, particles less closely packed), and gas (no definite shape or volume, particles far apart). Changes of state include: melting (solid to liquid), freezing (liquid to solid), evaporation (liquid to gas), condensation (gas to liquid), and sublimation (solid to gas directly). Physical changes are reversible with no new substance formed. Chemical changes produce new substances and are usually irreversible. The water cycle shows natural changes: evaporation, condensation, precipitation, and collection.",
    "rules": [
      "Solid: definite shape and volume",
      "Liquid: definite volume, takes container shape",
      "Gas: no definite shape or volume",
      "Melting: solid to liquid",
      "Freezing: liquid to solid",
      "Evaporation: liquid to gas",
      "Condensation: gas to liquid",
      "Sublimation: solid to gas directly",
      "Physical change: reversible, no new substance",
      "Chemical change: new substance formed, usually irreversible",
      "Water cycle: evaporation, condensation, precipitation, collection"
    ]
  },
